      "markdown": "Divisibilityand Primes \n\n### 1.1 Division Algorithm \n\nDivisibility is a fundamental concept in numbertheory. Let a and d be integers.tidivioofndthimltipleof $d,$  f there exists an integer q such that \n\n\n\n$$a=d q.$$\n\nIf d divides a, we write \n\n$$d|a.$$\n\nFor example,1001 is divisibleby7 and13. Divisibility istransitive:Ifa divides b and b divides c, then a divides c ViaCS0ad0diaCbOiean (Exercise 14).\n\nThe minimum principle tatesthat everyonemptytofintegersbounded below contains a smallest element. For example, a nonempty set of nonnegative integers must contain asmallest element.We can see the necessity of the condition that the nonempty set be bounded below by considering the example of the set 1aIirPCoU1CbCU $$ of all integers, positive, negative,and zero.EM \n\nThe minimum principle is all we needto prove the following important result.\n\n\n\nTheorem 1.1 (Division algorithm) Let a and d be integers with $d\\geq1$ There exist unique integers q andr such that 司\n\n$$a=d q+r $$\n\nand \n\n$$0\\leq r\\leq d-1.$$",
